#: admin/settings.php:363
msgid "Count successful lost-password requests"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:370
msgid "Count every submission, not just failed ones. Prevents an attacker from spamming reset emails to a known-valid address."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:377
msgid "Security Hardening"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:378
msgid "Modern protections against the most common automated attacks. The first two are safe on a typical site and are on by default."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:381
msgid "Block username enumeration"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:388
msgid "Stops attackers harvesting valid usernames: redirects ?author=N author scans and removes the REST /wp/v2/users listing for logged-out visitors. Author pages at /author/name/ keep working."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:393
msgid "Generic login errors"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:400
msgid "Show one neutral message instead of revealing whether the username or the password was wrong. Applies to wp-login.php and the plugin's own forms."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:405
msgid "Block breached passwords"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:412
msgid "Stop users from choosing a password found in a known data breach, checked at registration, password reset, and account update. Uses the Have I Been Pwned range API with k-anonymity — only the first 5 characters of the password's SHA-1 hash are sent, never the password. Fails open if the service is unreachable. Off by default because it contacts an external service."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:417
msgid "Disable XML-RPC"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:424
msgid "Turn off XML-RPC (xmlrpc.php) to close a common brute-force amplifier and pingback abuse. Leave OFF if you use Jetpack or the WordPress mobile app, which rely on it."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:431
msgid "Bot Protection (Cloudflare Turnstile)"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:432
msgid "Add a privacy-friendly Cloudflare Turnstile challenge to your forms to stop automated logins, fake registrations, and password-reset spam. Create a free widget in your Cloudflare dashboard under Turnstile, then paste the keys below."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:435
msgid "Enable Turnstile"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:442
msgid "Takes effect once both keys below are filled in."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:447
msgid "Site Key"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:450
msgid "The public site key from your Turnstile widget."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:455
msgid "Secret Key"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:459
msgid "Defined as ZENLOGAU_TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY in wp-config.php — manage it there."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:463
msgid "Stored encrypted (AES-256-GCM, keyed from your wp-config.php salts) and never shown again after saving."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:469
msgid "Protect which forms"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:485
msgid "The challenge appears on the selected forms — both the plugin's forms and the standard wp-login.php."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:492
#: includes/elementor/class-fauth-elementor-widgets.php:1634
#: includes/elementor/class-fauth-elementor-widgets.php:1889
#: includes/two-factor.php:455
msgid "Two-Factor Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:493
msgid "Let users add a second step at login with an authenticator app (TOTP). Each user turns it on for their own account from the Account page — there is nothing to configure here beyond the master switch. Recovery codes are provided for lost devices. Google sign-in is not affected."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:496
msgid "Enable two-factor authentication"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:503
msgid "When on, an \"Two-Factor Authentication\" section appears on the Account form so users can enroll. Turning this off stops the login challenge for everyone (existing enrollments are kept and resume if you turn it back on)."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:510
#: includes/elementor/class-fauth-elementor-widgets.php:1546
#: includes/elementor/class-fauth-elementor-widgets.php:1885
#: includes/passkeys.php:469
msgid "Passkeys"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:511
msgid "Let users sign in without a password using a passkey — fingerprint, face, screen lock, or a security key. Each user adds their own passkeys from the Account page. Passkeys are phishing-resistant and count as multi-factor, so a passkey sign-in skips both the password and any two-factor step. Requires HTTPS."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:514
msgid "Enable passkeys"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:521
msgid "Adds a \"Passkeys\" section to the Account form and a \"Sign in with a passkey\" button to the login form. Turning this off hides both; saved passkeys are kept and resume if you re-enable."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:528
msgid "New-Device Login Alerts"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:529
msgid "Email the account owner the first time their account is signed in from a browser or device the site has not seen before — like the \"new sign-in\" alerts from Google or GitHub. Sent with your site's normal email; no external service is used."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:532
msgid "Send new-device alerts"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:539
msgid "Recognises devices with a long-lived cookie. Clearing cookies counts as a new device, so an alert may be sent again."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:544
msgid "Custom email body"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:546
msgid "Leave blank to use the styled default message."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:548
msgid "Optional. Leave blank to send the styled default HTML message. Use INLINE styles only — e.g. <p style=\"color:#0369a1\">. Email clients ignore stylesheets, so <style> blocks, <head>, and <html>/<body> wrappers are removed automatically. These placeholders are replaced when the email is sent:"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:557
msgid "Login Activity"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:558
msgid "Records successful logins, failed attempts, and rate-limit lockouts so you can review them in the \"Login Activity\" widget on your WordPress dashboard. IP addresses are stored anonymised."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:561
msgid "Log login activity"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:568
msgid "Turn off to stop recording new events. Existing entries are kept until cleared or aged out."
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:573
msgid "Keep history for"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:575
msgid "days"
msgstr ""

#: admin/settings.php:576
msgid "Older entries are deleted automatically. Set to 0 to keep entries indefinitely (not recommended)."
msgstr ""

